\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
This paper presents Dual-Threshold Consistency and Backdoor Scrubbing (DTCBS), a robust training pipeline that leverages noisy and corrupted data while defending against malicious backdoor triggers. By integrating a two-stage consistency training process with a reverse-noise screening mechanism, DTCBS effectively mitigates the common limitations of ambient diffusion models, including training data memorization and susceptibility to adversarial attacks. Comprehensive experiments on CIFAR-10 and synthetic datasets demonstrated that DTCBS significantly improves the detection of malicious samples and enhances reconstruction quality relative to baseline methods. The iterative refinement process further stabilizes training by continuously updating the filtering criteria, ensuring that inconsistent or tampered inputs are progressively eliminated. Future research may focus on reducing the computational overhead associated with iterative filtering, extending the approach to handle linearly corrupted data, and incorporating additional security measures. Overall, DTCBS represents a significant advancement in developing secure and robust generative models under challenging conditions.

